_700x1050.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mG1zf0b6vRUWhGt4oEomnUR- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1wXy2GqdEvWqXGNwY4CiptsFkxs38QY4XwyQR190-6c=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMTUwNTAxNmMtYjg3Ny00MmUyLWE1Y2MtMWMzZTQ3MGNhYzgzXzcwMHgxMDUwLmpwZWc= 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="240" height="360" alt="Daughersofdecay Punchcards" title="Daughersofdecay Punchcards" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/YIfBgDSpfPoYjGq7Cfw8m- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/I0QcsczcCV1TFJbSqmdR6- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/oK2FsrzMECfcEtksv53QQdZsGhqeQbhswch75Z3_rKQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMTUwNTAxNmMtYjg3Ny00MmUyLWE1Y2MtMWMzZTQ3MGNhYzgzXzcwMHgxMDUwLmpwZWc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><a href="https://www.nms.ac.uk/explore-our-collections/stories/science-and-technology/jacquard-loom/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Jacquard loom program</a>.</figcaption></figure><p>There were also <a href="https://www.nms.ac.uk/explore-our-collections/stories/science-and-technology/jacquard-loom/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">the cards used to encode textile patterns with Jacquard looms</a> (which were an influence in the early history of computer programming<a id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1">1</a>):</p><blockquote><p>The mechanism involved the use of thousands of punch cards laced together. Each row of punched holes corresponded to a row of a textile pattern. This modification not only introduced greater efficiency to the weaving process, allowing the weaver to produce, unaided, fabrics with patterns of almost unlimited size and complexity, but also influenced the future development of computing technology.</p></blockquote><p>Returning to sewing machines and sewing patterns, not only did personalization arise, but the very <a href="https://reviews.history.ac.uk/review/1794" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">adaptation to new technology was vital</a>:</p><blockquote><p>Butterick, unlike European tailors, embraced the new technology â€“ in France sewing machines installed in 1840 to make uniforms for the French army were destroyed by tailors fearful of a future in which mechanized tailoring threatened their livelihoods and, for some years it was women who saw the many possibilities of sewing machines despite their high cost.</p></blockquote><p>In our modern era, sewing, personal computers, and patterns have even merged more explicitly, such as through <a href="https://www.joann.com/ditto/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Ditto</a>, a digital sewing pattern generator tool.</p><p>If any of you know more about this history or other interesting parallels between computing and sewingâ€”for example, how â€œpersonalâ€ were the early sewing machines?â€”I would love to know more. â– </p><p><a href="https://arbesman.substack.com/p/the-sewing-machine-as-personal-computer?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Share</a></p><h3>The Enchanted Systems Roundup</h3><p>Here are some links worth checking out that touch on the complex systems of our world (both built and natural):</p><p>ğŸœ¸ <em><a href="https://virginiaheffernan